  "prompt": "Are there legal obligations for financial institutions regarding money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, financial institutions have significant legal obligations to prevent, detect, and report money laundering. These typically include:\n\n1. Customer Due Diligence (CDD)\n- Verifying customer identities\n- Understanding the nature of customer business activities\n- Assessing potential money laundering risks\n\n2. Reporting Requirements\n- Reporting suspicious transactions\n- Filing Currency Transaction Reports (CTRs)\n- Maintaining transaction records\n\n3. Anti-Money Laundering (AML) Compliance Programs\n- Developing internal policies and procedures\n- Conducting employee training\n- Implementing monitoring systems\n\n4. Know Your Customer (KYC) Regulations\n- Collecting detailed customer information\n- Screening customers against watchlists\n- Performing ongoing customer risk assessments\n\n5. Legal Frameworks\n- Complying with national and international regulations\n- Following guidelines from organizations like FATF\n- Implementing robust internal control mechanisms\n\n6. Potential Penalties\n- Significant financial fines\n- Potential criminal liability\n- Loss of banking licenses\n\nThese obligations are designed to prevent financial crimes and protect the integrity of the global financial system.",
